SIMPLE: suffer
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Suffer
<hw>Suf"fer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Suffered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Suffering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>suffren</ets>, <ets>soffren</ets>, OF. <ets>sufrir</ets>,
<ets>sofrir</ets>, F. <ets>souffrir</ets>, (assumed) LL.
<ets>sofferire</ets>, for L. <ets>sufferre</ets>; <ets>sub</ets> under +
<ets>ferre</ets> to bear, akin to E. <ets>bear</ets>. See <er>Bear</er>
to support.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To feel, or endure, with pain,
annoyance, etc.; to submit to with distress or grief; to undergo;
<as>as, to <ex>suffer</ex> pain of body, or grief of
mind</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To endure or undergo without sinking; to support; to
sustain; to bear up under.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our spirit and strength entire,⟦br⟧
Strongly to <qex>suffer</qex> and support our pains.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To undergo; to be affected by; to sustain; to
experience; <as>as, most substances <ex>suffer</ex> a change when long
exposed to air and moisture; to <ex>suffer</ex> loss or
damage.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If your more ponderous and settled project⟦br⟧
May <qex>suffer</qex> alteration.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To allow; to permit; not to forbid or hinder; to
tolerate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt in any wise rebuke thy neighbour, and not
<qex>suffer</qex> sin upon him.</q> <rj><qau>Lev. xix.
17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>suffer</qex> them to enter and possess.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To permit; bear; endure; support; sustain; allow;
admit; tolerate. See <er>Permit</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suffer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Suffer
<hw>Suf"fer</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To feel or undergo
pain of body or mind; to bear what is inconvenient; <as>as, we
<ex>suffer</ex> from pain, sickness, or sorrow; we <ex>suffer</ex> with
anxiety</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O well for him whose will is strong!⟦br⟧
He <qex>suffers</qex>, but he will not <qex>suffer</qex> long.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To undergo punishment; specifically, to undergo the
penalty of death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The father was first condemned to <qex>suffer</qex> upon a day
appointed, and the son afterwards the day following.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be injured; to sustain loss or damage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Public business <qex>suffers</qex> by private infirmities.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sufferable</ent>⟦br⟧
